  "category_subtitle": "Learn how to count houses and buildings in Japanese using 軒",
  "category_detail": "<b>Counting Houses in Japanese</b><br><br>In Japanese, houses and buildings are counted using the counter <b>「軒」(けん / ken)</b>.<br><br>This counter is commonly used for <b>houses, shops, restaurants, and other buildings</b>.<br><br><b>Important Sound Changes</b><br>Some numbers change pronunciation when combined with 軒.<br><br><span class=\"example\">1軒</span> <span class=\"romaji\">(いっけん / ikken)</span><br><span class=\"example\">6軒</span> <span class=\"romaji\">(ろっけん / rokken)</span><br><span class=\"example\">8軒</span> <span class=\"romaji\">(はっけん / hakken)</span><br><span class=\"example\">10軒</span> <span class=\"romaji\">(じゅっけん / jukken)</span><br><br><b>Common Usage</b><br><span class=\"example\">この通りには家が三軒あります。</span> <span class=\"romaji\">(kono toori ni wa ie ga sanken arimasu)</span><br>Meaning: There are three houses on this street.<br><br>This counter is useful when talking about buildings in a neighborhood.",
